Red Wine Exploration

Josh Barros

January 24, 2018

This report explores a data set containing 1,599 bottles of red wine. The attributes describing the wine are as follows:

1 - fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

2 - volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

3 - citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines

4 - residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

5 - chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine

6 - free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

7 - total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

8 - density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

9 - pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

10 - sulfates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, which acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

11 - alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine output variable (based on sensory data).

12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The data set contains 1,599 different bottles of red wine. There are 11 variables describing the chemical content of the wine as well as 1 variable describing the quality.

What is the main feature of your dataset?

The main feature of my data set is how all the chemical variables support of hinder the “quality” of wine. So quality is my main feature.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I’m anxious to see how everything is correlated when I do the bi variate analysis.That should give me some insight to see how the chemical variables affect the quality.

Did you create any new variables in the dataset?

Yes, I changed the ‘quality’ variable from “int” to a factor variable.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributins? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust or change data? If so, why did you do this?

There were some very positively skewed distributions(chloride, residual sugar and total surfer dioxide).So I log-transformed the distributions so they can be more readable.

Bivariate Plots Section

We can see strong correlations both positive and negative in the correlation matrix.

I chose the variables above because of the strong positive correlation(fixed acidity, density) and strong negative correlation(fixed acidity, pH). Both are textbook examples.

We can see here that alcohol content has a positive correlation to the quality.

Sulfates also have kind of a linear relationship with quality.

Looks like volatile acid has a genitive correlation to the quality.

Citric acid is also showing a weak linear relationship to the quality.

Not seeing much from this chart.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature of interest vary with othe featuresin the dataset?

It was interesting to find out that alcohol, sulphates and citric acid were all positively correlated to the feature of interest “quality”.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features?

I thought the relationship between volatile acid and quality was interesting. It looks like with its strong negative correlation that the more acidic acid in the wine the worse rating it got.

What was the strongest relationship found?

The strongest relationship found was with fixed acidity and density. With a perfect looking linear regression chart to match.

Multivariate Plots

With this chart we can see a strong positive correlation with density and fixed acid. So it looks like density and fixed acidity have a strong influence on the quality of the wine.

Since alcohol and sulfates both had the highest positive correlations to quality, I wanted to see what it would look like on a chart.

Multivariable Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

The relationship between fixed acidity, density and alcohol was the most interesting relationship I think in this analysis.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

I was surprised that alcohol and sulphates didn’t have more of a positive linear regression line.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Plot Three

Reflection:

What I really learned in this project was how powerful R programming language is. Now I see why statistician’s like using R so much. It’s simple and straight forward and makes wonderful visualizations.

Now on to what I learned about the analysis of red wine. It wasn’t too surprising to see that the quality of wine followed a normal distribution, most of the bottles were around average quality. It’s really hard to make great wine. It was also interesting to see the correlations with fixed acidity and density as well as the relationship between alcohol and quality.

For future analysis I would like to compare the red wine analysis to an analysis of white wine and see how different or how much the results are the same.
